{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|す}}

{{unk|sort=す|ja}}. One theory is that this is a native Japanese term, with the ''su'' reading somehow related to the way that very sour things cause one to [[pucker]].

Given that vinegar was historically introduced to Japan in the 300-400s from China, another possibility is that the ''su'' reading is from {{der|ja|ltc|sort=す|-}} {{ltc-l|醋}} instead, with the {{m|ja|酢}} spelling as an example of {{juku|sort=す}}, and that this ''su'' reading [[naturalize]]d and came to be regarded as a native [[訓読み#Japanese|kun'yomi]] rather than a Chinese-derived [[音読み#Japanese|on'yomi]]. Compare modern {{cog|cmn|醋|tr=cù}} or {{cog|yue|醋|tr=cou<sup>3</sup>}}.

